Nov 14 2009 	Great location and excellent value	Booked this hotel back in the summer before it opened for a friends weekend in New York. Perfect location for plays, shopping, restaurants. Excellent breakfast. Rooms very clean and people at the desk were very friendly. Fantastic price for this location is New York City!	
Oct 31 2009 	Mad for Midtown	Overall, a very good place to stay in pricey, crowded, tourist-packed Midtown. Not an elegant hotel, but practical and relatively economical given NYC prices. The location is just a block away from the Majestic Theater, where &quot;Phantom of the Opera&quot; plays, and near many, many restaurants, bars, Starbucks, coffee shops and so on. But the block the hotel is on is a little quieter, or at least seemed that way on a weekend, with a parking garage across the street and a parking lot and residential buildings to the rear. We had a small but completely useful room on the sixth floor, with a view of skyscrapers and a window that actually opened. The queen bed more or less took up all the space, but I expect that in a NYC hotel. There was a desk with a light, and a small fridge, and a closet with an ironing board and hangers. The bathroom was incredibly clean - I think I am safe in saying I have never seen a hotel bathroom so clean and it is easy to tell because it is all white. If a clean hotel bathroom is important to you, then you have found your nirvana. I was surprised there wasn't any printed information about the hotel in the room, and no directions or guide for the television. There was not a lot of hot water when I showered, but it may be because it was a little late in the morning by the time we got going. For breakfast, there were croissants, muffins and pastries, scrambled eggs, bacon, bagels, cereal, coffee, juice and a waffle maker. We were satisfied. A very attentive staff member was stationed in the breakfast area and kept things stocked and the tables clean. The clerk at the front desk was pleasant and helpful though a little flustered when too many things happened at once. The hotel is a bit of a hike from Penn Station, about a 15-minute walk down crowded sidewalks, so if you are coming from there with a lot of suitcases you might want to hail a cab. The Port Authority subway entrance is just down the block and attractions like Madame Tussaud's and the theater district are very close. I would happily return, though the rate I paid was not the deep discount that others reported. I also would not be too excited about the basement rooms and would think they should charge less for those. Oh, and just one elevator, so you have to be a little patient, again usual for a NYC hotel.	
