Oct 28 2009 	Convenience and Value	Selected this hotel based on good reviews, price just under $200 and closeness to the theater district. In addition, Times Square is a fun area, close to restaurants and shopping and convenient to the subway. Although restaurant row is 8th Ave., my son and I found that 9th Ave. has tons of less expensive and just as good dining. The cab trip to the hotel from Laguardia Airport was $27 plus $4 toll plus tip.  The hotel itself was very comfortable and the staff very helpful. I was able to use the computer and printer in the business room most times when I wanted or had a short wait. Although it is a large hotel, the elevator was not slow or full. Check in and out was quick. The breakfast room staff was very good and kept the orange juice and coffee etc. flowing. A big plus is that the coffee in the breakfast room is available fresh all day! No need to use the in-room pot. The room also has it's own ironing board and iron and a hair dryer that works. The plus of the rooms is that they provide four comfy pillows per bed and the mattresses are good-not extra firm or too soft. We asked for a two bed room, which I later learned are all in a row on each floor and do not have a view of the street. The window is high anyway so it wasn't important and the location was very quiet. We were on the 6th floor and heard no traffic or neighbors. The only negatives we found was that the door to the bathroom was mostly glass and you could see through it! Amazing, huh?! We had brought a garment bag for wedding clothes and there was a hook over the door on the bathroom side that we could hang it and cover the glass. Otherwise no privacy in the bathroom-beware! Also, like most places, they could use an upgrade in toilet paper and tissue. I did like the design with the sink and mirror in the bathroom and not in the sleeping area. I would definately stay here again to be able to walk to the theater and dinner. The savings over comparable hotels is probably $50 a day. Great find!	
Oct 28 2009 	Not Bad if the Price is Right	I booked the Comfort Inn on 44th St. a few months ago, before they were even open, at a great rate of $129 per night. I think if I would have paid much more than that, I would not have been happy with this hotel. I arrived for a 4-night stay with a friend at about 12:30, and was given a double bed room on the second floor right away. Even the woman at the front desk made a comment about the good rate I got, and I know that it is much more expensive now that it is open and doing well.First off, the room was TINY. The 2 beds took up most of the room, but there was also a small desk and 2 chairs, a mini-fridge (which didn't work) and a cabinet with a couple drawers that also contained an iron and very small ironing board. The bathroom was also small, with one sink and not much space to put anything. I noticed that the metal sink supports were already starting to rust. Given that this hotel has only been open a couple months, it doesn't bode well for the future! The walls were very thin, and we actually had to call the front desk one night at 12:30 a.m. because we could hear a child in the next room very clearly. They did take care of the situation, and it was quiet shortly after.On a positive note, the beds were very comfortable, and housekeeping did a nice job; perhaps a little too nice, as the odor of Pine-Sol was overwhelming at times. We didn't have a lot of interaction with the front desk staff, but those we did deal with were friendly and helpful. We didn't experience the difficulty getting a table in the breakfast room that other reviews mentioned, and we were happy with the selection. It was described as a continental breakfast, but there was always either hard-boiled eggs or scrambled eggs and bacon, as well as cereals, fruit, yogurt, breads, bagels, croissants, danish and make-your-own waffles. We appreciated the savings in both money and time by having this available.The location was just OK. It was very close to 9th Ave. and many restaurants, but the walk to most subway lines (except for the A, C. and E, which was at the end of the street) was through the Times Square area and huge crowds of people. It was very close to the theaters, though, which was a plus if you plan to see a show.I would recommend this Comfort Inn only if you get a rate of $150-$175 or so. Anything higher than that is not worth it, in my opinion.	
Oct 23 2009 	Do you feel lucky?	This hotel has had some good reviews, but I have to go with my true feelings. I got a very cheap AAA rate, but my only description would be &quot;are you feeling lucky?&quot;. If you are, stay there. If you want to be sure of what you are getting yourself in for, don't stay here.New hotel. 7 floors plus the basement. 5 of the rooms are below ground level (not real good views I don't think), 5 rooms open straight off the lobby (they don't look too bad, but I wouldnt want the people in the lobby looking straight at my bed everytime I open my door). On each floor there are 7 good sized rooms, 2 smaller rooms, and one closet (I got one of those). So by my maths, there are about 42 good rooms, 12 okay rooms, 10 poorly located rooms, and 6 closets which are charged at the same rate as the rooms. Housekeeping - a bit hit and miss. Sometimes cleaner than others.The elevator broke down once during my stay, and I had heard of it happening before. Just a concern that with only one elevator if anything goes awry, it can be a long walk. Coffee and breakfast are available in the front room (you can sit here and watch people go straight in and out of their rooms for entertainment). Breakfast basic, but fine for the price. Coffee is available (but only when staff want to fill the pot), Several times when I went to avail of the coffee, the pot was empty - when I asked staff about it they said it would be done immediately - immediately can be two or more hours - don't expect it quickly.Room size - well some are very good, but if you stay here just hope you don't get one of the small ones. There is about 4 inches between the corner of the bed and the fridge, so if you want to get to the small desk, the small closet, or the window (doesnt apply to the rooms in the basement) you have to step over the bed or fridge. Yes - that small.Unfortunately by way of averages, if the people who got the tiny rooms reflect that in their reviews, they will be overwhelmed by those who got a decent room. So - 'Are you feeling lucky?&quot;	
