Sep 24 2009 	Basic no frills accomodations in the Theater District	I got a great AAA rate at this property of $117/night by booking a few months in advance before the hotel had even opened for business. Given that the UN General Assembly was in session at the time of my stay, this was an unheard of bargain for that week in NYC. However, even at that price and the fact that the hotel was less than a month old, I was less than thrilled with property and with my stay there.Rooms are of decent size for accomodations of this class/price in Manhattan, with the sleeping area probably 200-225 sq ft. I had a room with 2 double beds (other rooms have only 1 queen bed). The bathroom was very small (the door barely cleared the toilet) but the vanity was spacious compared to other comparable properties I've stayed at in Manhattan. Upon walking into my room, my partner immediately noticed trash left behind (an empty carton of cigarettes and a soft drink cup were sitting on top of the closet unit). Otherwise, the room was clean--but I found this oversight by the cleaning staff unacceptable.Beds were new and comfortable. I didn't like that the hotel uses bedspreads instead of the more popular double sheet/duvet covers in vogue these days at better properties. Bedspreads are not very sanitary (hotels rarely wash them), but since the hotel was less than a month old, I wasn't too grossed out (there weren't any visible stains). Sheets were a bit rough and scratchy. Pillows were ample (and feather-free). Towels were absorbent and soft and of decent quality for a hotel of this class.HVAC worked well in the room. I was on the 6th floor facing 44th St and had few issues with noise but I'm used to living in NYC. The fridge and microwave ovens originally advertised by the hotel apparently are not going to be included in the rooms, or at least weren't at this time. My room lacked a desk and instead had a small square table that substituted for one. It had two arm chairs when it would have been better equipped with one desk chair and one arm chair. Oh, well. TV worked well overall and had reasonable channel selections. Wireless internet was free and worked well when I used it. Coffee machine and ice bucket in room were a plus (ice free in basement). There is only one elevator for this 7 story building.Free breakfast was very basic and nothing to get excited over--cheap carbs to get you moving in the morning. Hours were rather limited as was the seating area. Breakfast consisted of coffee, juices, sugary cereals, some breads/bagels/pastries of mediocre quality and make your own waffles. The breakfast area was kept stocked the three mornings I was at the hotel.Considering the hotel was less than a month old, it didn't seem like it was new, although it was generally clean and modern in appointments. I question whether over time this property will hold up. Hallways and rooms didn't appear to be vacuumed daily, and some of the dirt/mess from construction was never cleaned up. Housekeeping was a bit rude and not the best in the industry. This appears to be a family run property.Would I stay here again? Well, likely not. I think there are better managed properties, and cleaner, more pleasing properties, at comparable pricepoints in Manhattan if you do your research. Perhaps I've been spoiled by some great deals at better properties in Manhattan during this recession. But now that the economy is turning around, the days of decent hotel rooms in NYC under $200/night might be coming to an end.	
Sep 17 2009 	Simple hotel in a great location	I booked our room a few months ago before knowing the hotel was not open. I luckily discovered the hotel opened a week before it was scheduled to, around August 25th. My sister and I stayed from Sept 8 to the 11 to go to the US Open in Queens. We checked in and asked for a room on the back side as we noticed construction on 44 st. We were given a room on the 4th floor. The room was small but it had two double beds, a flat screen TV, end table, and two chairs. The bathroom was a good size, much bigger then the bathroom I had at the Comfort Inn on the Upper West Side. As other reviewers note, they use bed spreads in this hotel and my sister told me they can get very very dirty as they are never cleaned. We removed them and stored them in the corner. The elevator was out once as it was being worked on but the stairs to the 4th floor was easy enough, with out luggage. Hopefully, the single elevator is working well by now.There was a domestic disturbance going on in the next room over so I called the front desk. Someone came up and asked if everything was okay and the participants quieted down or left. The event was well handled by the staff. Breakfast; bagels, croissants, and other pastries. They have a waffle machine which made tasty waffles. Coffee, juice, and water were available. Currently, there are not enough tables. So, you might have to wait until one is free. Hotel recommendation; replace some smaller tables with bigger ones. People will eat together, even strangers.Little things were nice; free wifi and each lamp had an outlet built into it, so no need to unplug the lamp to recharge the cell phone or laptop.Location; 10 minute walk to Time Square, 10 minutes to the Penn Authority bus terminal. 20 minutes from Penn Station rail stop.Over all pleasant stay at a great rate of $140 a night. I believe this was a promo rate for the opening of the hotel but I am not sure.Eric	
